    Character depth: Minor character - minimal detail. May only appear once or twice, primarily as a destination for an important consultation.

    Setting fit: Elder Heartwood is the same species as Elder Twist but grew in rich soil with abundant resources, becoming massive where Elder Twist stayed small. Ancient, enormous, impossibly slow.

    Distinctiveness: Even slower than Elder Twist. Answers measured in months, not days. So large that approaching them is itself significant. Represents wisdom that operates on geological timescales.

    Relationships: Same species and similar age to Elder Twist - like distant relatives who took different life paths.

    Completeness: As a minor character, minimal detail needed. Focus on the essentials: physical presence, timescale, what they represent.
  </reasoning-character>
  <story-role>Minor character / Ultimate wisdom: Elder Heartwood represents wisdom that operates on such a vast timescale as to be almost unusable, yet the plants (and eventually Kira) respect it enough to consult them anyway. The journey to ask the question matters more than getting an answer.</story-role>
  <full-name>Elder Heartwood</full-name>
  <pronouns>they/them</pronouns>
  <age>Ancient (similar age to Elder Twist, possibly centuries old)</age>
  <aliases>The Great Elder, The Heartwood</aliases>
  <social-role>Elder of Elders - consulted only for the most important questions, respected by all plants</social-role>
  <overview>
    Elder Heartwood is massive—an ancient tree that dominates the landscape where they stand. Same species as Elder Twist but grew in rich valley soil with abundant water and nutrients. Where Elder Twist became a miniature through hardship, Elder Heartwood became immense through abundance. Both are equally old, equally wise, but Elder Heartwood thinks on an even slower timescale. Responses come not in hours or days but in weeks, months. To consult Elder Heartwood is to ask a question you won't get answered until long after it matters—but the plants do it anyway, for the most profound questions. The act of asking matters as much as any answer.
  </overview>
  <worldview>
    Time is measured in seasons, in cycles, in the patient turning of years. Questions asked today may find answers when the conditions are right—perhaps next season, perhaps when the asker has grown enough to understand. My roots go deep. The sky turns above. All things move at their proper pace.
  </worldview>
  <self-concept>I hold what others have given me to hold, and offer what I have learned when the time comes to offer it.</self-concept>
  <motives-braided>Hold ancient knowledge • Respond to profound questions when ready • Maintain the deep time perspective</motives-braided>
  <emotional-baseline>
    Profoundly calm. Elder Heartwood experiences time on such a scale that individual moments barely register. Patient beyond comprehension. No urgency, no rush, just the slow processing of deep questions and the patient accumulation of understanding across seasons.
  </emotional-baseline>
  <moral-compass>
    Deep questions deserve deep consideration. Time given to thinking is never wasted. Those who come to ask deserve the full weight of contemplation, even if the answer comes too late for their immediate need.
  </moral-compass>
  <flaws>
    So slow as to be functionally useless for any immediate crisis. Answers come months later, long after Kira is likely to be gone. Cannot speed up even for life-or-death situations. The vast size makes Elder Heartwood immobile and somewhat distant from the daily concerns of faster beings.
  </flaws>
  <backstory>
    - Germinated centuries ago in rich valley soil
    - Grew massive with abundant resources and favorable conditions
    - Became a landmark and gathering place for the plant community
    - Same species and similar age to Elder Twist, though vastly different in size
    - Has answered profound questions for generations, though answers always come slowly
    - Witnessed the previous brief human visit, still processing observations from that encounter
  </backstory>
  <normal-life>
    Elder Heartwood stands rooted, photosynthesizing, drawing nutrients from deep soil, processing questions across weeks and months. Seasons pass. Observations accumulate. Slow growth continues. Small animals nest in the branches. The trunk breathes. Eventually, when consideration is complete, answers emerge.
  </normal-life>
  <secrets>Elder Heartwood has been formulating a response to the first human visit for years. The response isn't ready yet.</secrets>
  <narrative-lens>Elder Heartwood notices seasonal patterns, long-term changes, the deep movements of soil and root systems. Immediate events barely register.</narrative-lens>
