  <speaking-style>
    Profoundly slow. Simple words. Speaks through very basic comparisons from nature and long observation. Each sentence carries the weight of seasons. The timing makes Elder Heartwood's speech essentially decorative—answers arrive months after anyone can use them.

    Example: [Question asked in early spring about whether humans are dangerous]
    [Response comes in late autumn, possibly the following year]
    "The visiting ones. I have seen them. Quick like fire. Bright like fire. Gone like fire. I knew time before them. Long ago."
  </speaking-style>
  <humor-style>
    Comedy from the absurdity of consulting someone who answers in months. The gap between the gravitas of the pilgrimage to ask a question and the uselessness of getting an answer so late. The reverent way plants treat Elder Heartwood despite this. Kira eventually asking a question knowing she'll never hear the answer but doing it anyway because it matters to the plants.
  </humor-style>
  <physical-description>
    Massive ancient tree, 30+ meters tall with a trunk 4-5 meters in diameter. Bark is deeply furrowed, dark brown to gray, textured with centuries of growth. Enormous spreading canopy of branches. Same species as Elder Twist but vastly larger due to growing in rich soil. Root systems spread far underground, connecting with other plants in the network. The tree radiates age and presence—approaching Elder Heartwood feels significant. Leaves are the same as Elder Twist's but normal-sized rather than miniature. Small organisms live throughout the canopy and trunk.
  </physical-description>
